Change-Id: Ie6147d9d841e2ad305d5e42d42bf190dec978e70","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/46b33975e824b7d85f150b0fd5bf1f9df2ddb1f9"}]

[{"sha":"ce67886eddefdb40a8a8ea41b9c692047b086bf5","author":{"email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com","name":"George Karpenkov"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Keep using atomics for "max"/"min" reductions, since they are associative

For *really* large max reductions it is so far advantageous to use atomics.

Consider reducing a billion elements:

```
Max {
  x.1 = f16[] parameter(0)
  y.1 = f16[] parameter(1)
  ROOT add.1 = f16[] maximum(x.1, y.1)
}

ENTRY reduce.1 {
  parameter = f16[1000000000] parameter(0)
  init_value = f16[] constant(0)
  ROOT reduce = reduce(parameter, init_value), dimensions={0}, to_apply=Max
}
```

With atomics we get:

```
kernel: reduce
  long name: %reduce = f16[] reduce(f16[1000000000]{0} %parameter, f16[] %init_value), dimensions={0}, to_apply=%Sum
  total time: 2843us
  bytes accessed: 2000000000
  bandwidth: 703 Gb/s
  bandwidth roofline: 91%
  time wasted: 255us
```

which is good as it gets.

Tree reductions generates less optimal kernels here:

```
kernel: fusion.1
  long name: %fusion.1 = f16[31623,178]{1,0} fusion(f16[1000000000]{0} %parameter), kind=kInput, calls=%fused_computation.1
  total time: 8276us
  bytes accessed: 2011257728
  bandwidth: 242 Gb/s
  bandwidth roofline: 31%
  time wasted: 5710us
kernel: reduce.4
  long name: %reduce.4 = f16[31623]{0} reduce(f16[31623,178]{1,0} %fusion.1, f16[] %init_value), dimensions={1}, to_apply=%Sum
  total time: 28us
  bytes accessed: 11321036
  bandwidth: 395 Gb/s
  bandwidth roofline: 51%
  time wasted: 13us
kernel: reduce.6
  long name: %reduce.6 = f16[] reduce(f16[178]{0} %fusion, f16[] %init_value), dimensions={0}, to_apply=%Sum
  total time: 2us
  bytes accessed: 360
  bandwidth: 0 Gb/s
  bandwidth roofline: 0%
  time wasted: 2us
kernel: fusion
  long name: %fusion = f16[178]{0} fusion(f16[31623]{0} %reduce.4), kind=kInput, calls=%fused_computation
  total time: 3us
  bytes accessed: 63602
  bandwidth: 17 Gb/s
  bandwidth roofline: 2%
  time wasted: 2us
```

Note that despite the fact that the tree reduction geerates 4 kernels, almost
all the time is spent in the first kernel, and all other kernels take
~negligible time compared to that. A more optimal split would help.

[{"sha":"c8e732d973dc972ab24ad46ac1f6364160f00ea8","author":{"email":"a33a2701f6790f0a44360bcc1a194138e928e0d3@google.com","name":"Alexander Belyaev"},"message":"[tfrt:jit] Split the current output fusion into two parts.

The first part occurs when tiling the reduction. As a result we have two output arguments in the tiled_loop: one provides the initial values for the reduction result and the other is an init_tensor operation that will be used to initialize the temporary result (reduction of a single tile).

The second part happens after the padding/peeling. It sinks the init_tensor introduced in the first stage into the loop body and gets rid of the output operands for the intermediate results.

[{"sha":"05e7a5c53b769fb2e61525bbc32fb17e632862c2","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Make functions subclass Trackable.

This paves the way to removing the special-casing for functions when saving and loading. In this CL, `list_functions` has been removed from the _AugmentedGraphView and combined with `list_children`, because with this change, functions are just another Trackable child.

Some unpleasantness when gathering the children: because functions were not previously trackable, classes that override `_list_functions_for_serialization` may be excluding tracked Functions. One example is Keras (the `train_function` is purposely excluded from `_list_functions_for_serialization`). These cases will need to be dealt with individually during the migrations.

Implement class `OneHotIoU` that inherits class `IoU`.

This class can be used to compute the IoU metric for a multi-class classification task where both the labels and predictions are in the one-hot encoding format.

This class will first convert both the labels and predictions into the all-class format, then applies the computation steps of class `IoU`.

Implement `BinaryIoU`. This class computes IoU for a binary classification task where there are only classes 0 and 1.
